# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The solution involves a simple **iteration of the integer**, we can achive this result by using **Bitwise and Bitshift** operators [i.e. & and >>>] (*Look the note section for other technique*). These operators are faster, give you a precise control over individual bits of a number and are kinda cute when you understand them :D 

*At each iteration* we have to do Three operations:
1) If the **number is odd** there is a '1' in the last right position, we have to count it;
2) **Shift the number** right by one position, it will remove the most right '1' and add a '0' at the most left position;
3) If the **number is zero** this mean I have no other one to fint.

**Note:** Is possible to solve the problem using a **simpler approach** such as `n % 2 == 0` to check if the last bit is zero or one and using `n = n / 2` to make the shift.

**Bitwise AND (&):** It returns bit by bit AND of input values [i.e. if both bits are 1, it gives 1, else it shows 0].
**Unsigned Right shift operator (>>>):** Is used to shift the bits of a number right, thereby dividing the number by two. (From left add zeros)

# Complexity
- **Time complexity:** $O(n)$
- **Speed Beats:** 100%
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- **Space complexity:** $O(1)$
- **Memory Beats:** 94.18%
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

