**Explanation**

* Set the count to zero.
* If n is greater than 0, it means it enters the while loop.
* It uses the bitwise And operator(&) to check if n ==1.
* If it is true, it means increaments count value.
* Shifts the n value to the right extent using the right shift operator.
* Finally, return the counted value.

***Diagrammatic representation***
	![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/0add3b48-7733-4aa9-88c6-901a40a912df_1650185867.5690596.png)

```
class Solution {
public:
    int hammingWeight(uint32_t n) {
        int count=0;
        while(n>0){
            if(n&1)
                count++;
            n=n>>1;
        }
        return count;
    }
};
```

