solutions.content:
Explanation : 
'*' can act as '(' , ')' ,''
Create Two stacks
open :  for storing the indices of '(' ,and 
ast   :  for storing the indices of '*'
We will solve the Problem in two stages :
#1 STAGE:
here we consider '*' also as an opening paranthesis IF open stack becomes empty
steps:
Traverse over the string:
  for any character s[i] , i being its index
*   if   s[i] == '('
       push i in open stack
*  if s[i] == '*'
      push i in ast stack
* if s[i] == ')'
     > pop one elements from open stack
	  but if open stack is empty :
	 > pop one element from ast stack
	  but if ast stack is also empty , return false

After traversing all the characters, comes Second stage:
#2 STAGE:
Here we consider '*' as a closed paranthesis
Until open or ast stack becomes empty perform:
* if index at top of open stack > index at top of ast stack, this means there was no '*' after the last '(' , so return false
* otherwise pop one element from both open and ast stack

finally check if open stack is empty,
if YES then we were able to balance the complete string , return TRUE
else return FALSE

CODE:
```
bool checkValidString(string s) {
      stack<int> open,ast;
      for(int i=0;i<s.length();i++)
      {
          if(s[i] == ')')
          {
              if(!open.empty()) open.pop();
              else if(!ast.empty()) ast.pop();
              else return false;
          }
          else if(s[i] == '(')   open.push(i);
