Idea:
Based on the original idea (attached below), we can simply get rid of stack and use a variable `stack` to replace the stack.  

```
class Solution {
    public boolean checkValidString(String s) {
        int len = s.length(), stack = 0, left = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
            char c = s.charAt(i);
            if (c == '(') {
                stack += 1;
            } else if (c == ')') {
                if (stack != 0) {
                    stack -= 1;
                } else if (left > 0){
                    left -= 1;
                } else {
                    return false;
                }
            } else {
                if (stack != 0) {
                    stack -= 1;
                    left += 1;
                } 
                left += 1;
            }
        }
        if (stack == 0) {
            return true;
        } 
        return false;
    }
}
```


---
Original Post: One stack solution with O(n) time and one pass  

Idea:  
1. Never push `')'` to stack
2. Never push `'*'` to stack
3. The stack only contains `'('` if it isn't empty 
4. Use `left` to count potential `'('`  before following `')'` , to offset following `')'` 
(where potential `'('` means `'*'` or `'('` popped because of `'*'`)
```
class Solution {
    public boolean checkValidString(String s) {
        int len = s.length(), left = 0;
        Stack <Character> stack = new Stack();
        for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
            char c = s.charAt(i);
            if (c == '(') {
                stack.push(c);
            } else if (c == ')') {
                if (!stack.isEmpty()) {
                    stack.pop();
                } else if (left > 0){
                    left -= 1;
                } else {
                    return false;
                }
            } else {
                if (!stack.isEmpty()) {
                    stack.pop();
                    left += 1;
                } 
                left += 1;
            }
        }
        if (stack.isEmpty()) {
            return true;
        } 
        return false;
    }
}
```

