solutions.content:
using two stacks to record the index of `(` and `*`
1. we push the index to s1 if  `(` occurent and  push the index to s2 if `*` occurent
2. if `)` occurent, we try to pop the last `(` first, if s1 is empty which mean there are no `(` anymore. we try to use  `*`  replace `(`. we return False when both of s1 and s2 are empty
3. After go throught the string, we need to analyse the position of rest of `(`, we need one `*` with larger index for each `(`.
``` python
class Solution:
    def checkValidString(self, s: str) -> bool:
        if not s:
            return True
        s1 = []
        s2 = []
        for i in range(len(s)):
            if s[i] == "(":
                s1.append(i)
            elif s[i] == "*":
                s2.append(i)
            elif s[i] == ")":
                if s1:
                    s1.pop(-1)
                else:
                    if s2:
                        s2.pop(-1)
                    else:
                        return False
        while s1:
            if not s2:
                return False
            else:
                if s1.pop(-1) >s2.pop(-1):
                    return False
        return True

```

