solutions.content:
This solution is based on a key observation: **if a parenthesis string is valid, then it's still valid when "mirrored"** (read backwards, and replace `(` by `)` and `)` by `(`).

First write a simple & intuitive algorithm to handle `)`. It's not yet possible to rule out cases like `()*((*`.

Then "mirror" the string. The example is now `*))*()`, and it can be ruled out by the same algorithm as the first pass.

Since we've handled imbalances caused by both `(` and `)`, this algorithm should have eliminated all invalid strings.

```
class Solution {
public:
    bool checkValidString(string s) {
        // a = asterisk, d = depth
        int a = 0, d = 0, n = s.length();

        // First Pass
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            if (s[i] == '(') d++;
            else if (s[i] == '*') a++;
            else {
                if (d > 0) d--;
                else if (a > 0) a--; // Turn one of *'s into (
                else return false;
            }
        }
        if (d==0) return true;
        if (a<d) return false;

        // Second Pass
        d=a=0;
        for (int i = n-1; i >= 0; --i) {
            if (s[i] == ')') d++;  // DIFFERENT
            else if (s[i] == '*') a++;
            else {
                if (d > 0) d--;
                else if (a > 0) a--; // Turn one of *'s into )
                else return false;
            }
        }
        if (d==0) return true;
        if (a<d) return false;
        return true;
    }
};
```

Finally, the two loops can be merged, making it a single-pass algorithm.

