# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->The code then iterates through each character in the input string using a for loop. Here's what happens inside the loop:

If the current character is '(', it means an open parenthesis is encountered. In this case, both leftmin and leftmax are incremented by 1 since we have one more open parenthesis.

If the current character is ')', it means a closing parenthesis is encountered. In this case, both leftmin and leftmax are decremented by 1 since we have matched one open parenthesis with a closing one.

If the current character is neither '(' nor ')', it means it is an asterisk (*), which can represent either an open parenthesis, a closing parenthesis, or an empty string. In this case, leftmin is decremented by 1 (considering it as a closing parenthesis) and leftmax is incremented by 1 (considering it as an open parenthesis).

After updating the leftmin and leftmax variables, the code checks two conditions:

If leftmax becomes negative at any point during the iteration, it means we have encountered more closing parentheses than the possible open parentheses, which makes the expression invalid. In that case, the function returns false.

If leftmin becomes negative at any point during the iteration, it means we have encountered more closing parentheses than the open parentheses available so far. To keep leftmin non-negative, it is set to 0, assuming all the extra closing parentheses are balanced by open parentheses.

Finally, outside the loop, the code checks if leftmin is equal to 0. If it is, it means all open parentheses have been matched and canceled out by the corresponding closing parentheses, and there are no unmatched parentheses left. In that case, the function returns true. Otherwise, it returns false.

