solutions.content:
in this problem, we try to use a greedy kind of an algorithm

we have two stacks , one for the opening brackets ['('] and one for the stars (*)

whenever we encounter an opening bracket, we push its index into the openingBracket stack
whenever we encounter a star (*), we push it into the star stack
now whenever we encounter a closing bracket, we try to balance it with an opening bracket firstso for this we check the opening braket stack first, and if it has some index in it, we pop it (that is, that openingbracket will be used to balance this closing bracket)

but in case the opening bracket stack is empty, we look into the star stack,
we pop out the top element (signifying that this star (*) will now be used to balance this closing bracket)

in case both the stacks are empty, it means that we have no one to balance this closing bracket, and we will
have to return false


at the end, there will be some elements left out in both the stacks
but the important one is the opening bracket stack. the left out ones are those opening brackets, which
never got balanced by any closing bracket. so these left out opening brackets, have only one hope left : i.e
only stars (*) can balance them out by behaving like closing brackets

so while both stacks are non empty, keep popping the top guys from both of them
now for a star to balance out an opening bracket, it is obvious that it should come after the opening bracket

so in case the index of star is less than index of opening bracket, return false, because this star wont be able to balance it
(we return false, because all the subsequent stars which we encouter would have an even lower index, because of the order in which the elements are
	getting pushed)

at the end, we return true, only if the opening bracket stack is empty()
	the stars which remain in the star stack, would behave like empty strings

```


class Solution {
public:
	bool checkValidString(string s) {

		stack<int> leftBracketStack;
		stack<int> starStack;
		int len = s.length();

		for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
			if (s[i] == '(') leftBracketStack.push(i);
			else if (s[i] == '*') starStack.push(i);
			else {
				if (leftBracketStack.empty() && starStack.empty()) return false;

				if (leftBracketStack.size()) leftBracketStack.pop();
				else starStack.pop();
			}
		}


		while (!leftBracketStack.empty() && !starStack.empty()) {
			int leftBracketIndex = leftBracketStack.top(); leftBracketStack.pop();
			int starIndex = starStack.top(); starStack.pop();
			if (leftBracketIndex > starIndex) return false;
		}

		return leftBracketStack.empty();


	}
};



```

